### Page 150

Here is how to derive (5.51).

From (5.34) and (5.36), we have

$$\Gamma(k) = -i \sqrt{2} e^2 \sigma^i \epsilon^i.$$

Then we have, from (5.50)

$$
\begin{eqnarray}
  &&  \mathrm{tr} \left( \frac{\Gamma(k)\dot {\mathbf{n}^*}^j \sigma^j}{\sqrt{2}i} \right)  \\
  &=& - e^2 \mathrm{tr} \left( \mathbf{\epsilon}^i {\mathbf{n}^*}^j \sigma^i \sigma^j \right)  \\
  &=& - e^2 \mathrm{tr} \left( \mathbf{\epsilon}^i {\mathbf{n}^*}^j (\delta^i_j + i \epsilon_{ijk} \sigma^k) \right)  \\
  &=& - e^2 \mathrm{tr} \left( \mathbf{\epsilon}^i {\mathbf{n}^*}^i + i \epsilon_{ijk} \mathbf{\epsilon}^i {\mathbf{n}^*}^j \sigma^k) \right)
\end{eqnarray}
$$

Since the trace of all sigma matrices is 0, the trace of the second part is 0 and we have

$$\mathrm{tr} \left( \frac{\Gamma(k)\dot {\mathbf{n}^*}^j \sigma^j}{\sqrt{2}i} \right) = - 2e^2 \mathbf{\epsilon}^i {\mathbf{n}^*}^i.$$

