  &=& \frac{1}{\sqrt{m}} \int \frac{d^3k}{(2\pi)^3} \frac{1}{2\sqrt{2}} (4i \frac{e^2}{m}) \left( 2\psi_1(\mathbf{k}) k^x + 2\psi_2(\mathbf{k}) k^y \right)  \\
  &=& \sqrt{\frac{\pi\alpha^7}{2}} m.
\end{eqnarray}
$$

By summing up $$\gamma_+\gamma_-$$ and $$\gamma_-\gamma_+$$ and averaging over the five $$J_z$$s, we have
$$\Gamma(P_{J=2}\rightarrow 2\gamma) = \frac{1}{160}\alpha^7 m$$.

It is very nice to see that $$i\hat{\mathcal{M}}(P \rightarrow 2\gamma)$$ is non-zero only when $$J_z$$ is conserved.

